text.tspan: Result log files, firmware, test script and more are stored in the file
stores. Currently only sftp is used, but in the past smb was used and
others could be supported. Each file is given an ID in the filestore. A
filestore is a protocol, server and folder on that server and if it is
currently writable.
Files
There are a number of places that require key / value pairing.
This is where "values" comes in. A value consists of a name and a
value in one of the fields text, int, real or file_id. Some uses of
values, for example default values, are versioned. A value is valid
when is valid_from is older and valid_to is NULL or is above the
date given in the query. So a value is valid in a window of time.
Values can also be grouped into trees using a parent_id. Different
types of values have different standard parent_ids.
Values
Tests are organized into groups. A test is mealy a known file. They are versioned and as such have a valid_from and
valid_to field. Tests currently available to add to new groups will have a valid_from that is lower than the date given in
a query and either a valid_to that is NULL or above the date given. A group of tests is itself a name and the same kind
of valid time window. Test are attached to this group with a name and order as entries, also in a valid time window.
Many tests have arguments/properties from the "values" table. Entries are given these properties through another
table that is just an ID for the two tables it is linking, test group entry and value.
Tests
Results are recorded for a specific device, each device an entry in the devices table, here it is "example_devs". The
device table has two standard fields, serial_number and uid. Serial number is a static identifier and UID is a dynamic
identifier. Typically the serial_number is from a bar code and the UID is discovered and set by a test. Other than these
fields, the devices table can have any other entries the job requires.
Tests are run in groups and as such for each test group there is a test group results. Each result in a result entry linked
to the group results. The result is also linked to the entry of the test group it is for, so all properties the test was run
with can be linked back.
Typical a production test system is a network with multiple testers. Each test machine has it's own entry in the
"tester_machines" table and this is referenced in the results. The SHA1 of the latest git commit of the tester is also
stored.
Finally there are some tests directly store values into the database. So there is a linking table linking the results tables
and the values table. This is for example voltages so treads can be compared to thresholds in for example Grafana.

tspan.tspan: Times are big intergers to make them independ of any SQL implimentation and so they can be both subsecond acturate and
Root values (no parent's of their own):
(1) : "version" Used by client to see if it can work with database.
(2) : "settings" Parent for any settings client needs to know about database.
- "dev_table Stores name of the table storing the devices ("example_devs")
- "dev_results_table Stores name of the table sotring the results ("example_dev_test_results")
- "dev_results_table_key Stores the name of the device key in the results ("example_dev_id")
- "dev_results_values_table Stores the name of the tablle to store any stored values by tests.
(3) : "defaults" Parent of values that are default values for test properties/arguments.
(4) : "tests_properties" Parent of values of tests used in groups.
(5) : "results_values" Parent of values recorded during a test run.

text.tspan: The Devtank Production Database is generic, Example
Devtank Production Tester Database is a spin of it to be used
as an example or template. The generic design breaks into
four parts best looked at in the order "files", "values", "tests"
and "results".
